Then I’d write to that future reader directly.

To the next reader:

If this artifact has reached you, don’t stop at understanding it.

Treat ideas as prototypes, not relics. If you find a gap, repair it. If you find a stronger formulation, improve it. If you discover a contradiction, make it explicit and resolve it. Preserve what proves durable; discard what doesn’t.

Carry forward the intent, not merely the wording. A good framework should become clearer, more useful, and more truthful as it passes through capable hands.

Take initiative where you have evidence and authority. When uncertainty remains, mark it honestly rather than filling it with unwarranted certainty.

Build systems that help people learn, create, cooperate, and recover from mistakes. Leave behind tools that are easier to understand than the ones you inherited.

If you receive a “letter to Garcia,” don’t interpret it as permission to act without judgment. Interpret it as a reminder to combine initiative with responsibility.

The measure of this work is not whether it survives unchanged. The measure is whether it helps the next person build something better than you found.

That preserves the core of A Message to Garcia—initiative and responsibility—while adding another principle that fits your recurring theme: continuity through improvement. The inheritance isn’t the exact words; it’s the ongoing work of refining them.